		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Labyrinth was a complex structure created in the Greek mythology. It was built for the Minoan King to hold the Minotaur, the legendary bull monster which was eventually killed by the hero Theseus, the mythical king of Athens. The labyrinth was a confusing structure and Theseus had to mark his way through the labyrinth to find his way to the Minotaur and was able to come back out of it. Even though the word maze is synonymous with labyrinth they are not exactly the same thing. Though just as confusing, a maze may have many different branches that lead to the center of the puzzle, a labyrinth has a single path to the center. There are a few labyrinth-like structures in the island of Crete that led to many debates about the possible actual location of the labyrinth that held the Minotaur. However, historians came to the conclusion that although these structures can be the inspiration to the story, the Labyrinth and the Minotaur are indeed are a part of mythology rather than history.
			</p>
